by A m e n r i a » Wed May 19, 2021 11:02 am

Valentine Z wrote:Burmese: Amateurs.

(Image)

Seriously, my native language can be... utterly confusing. For one, there is this thing called "Written is one meaning, spoken is another," which more or less means that if you speak something literally as written in text, chances are good that the pronunciation can drastically change the meaning.

10 things I hate about the Burmese Language wrote:Oddballs: Words that are pronounced very differently from their spelling
Burmese has a number of words (usually loaned or commonly used ones) whose pronunciations don’t correspond to their spellings. A big example (at least to me) is the word ‘mint,’ (as in mint leaves) which is pronounced pu-si-nan but spelled pu-di-na (ပူဒီနာ). Maybe it’s because the word is originally Hindi. Another is the word ‘turmeric’, which is pronounced sa-nwin but spelled na-nwin (နနွင်း). How did the ‘n’ became an ‘s’?

Going back to the topic, yeah other than the pre-title and some odd bits here and there, you don't seem me using Burmese a lot in my factbooks, the reasons are two-fold:
- You probably cannot see it. It will end up as squares for about 70% of you, I am confident. I could turn them into screenshots, though.
- Valentine Z's national language is a conlang made out of 40+ languages, so it might not make a lot of sense to use Burmese. Maybe I could have my characters speaking one, without making it cringy.


I did hear Burmese is one of, if not the hardest language to learn.

by Altenkreis » Wed May 19, 2021 7:04 pm

My least favourite cliche would have to be nations made for power trips in general. I like the idea of a space empire that can devour worlds, but, maybe try to punch in your own weight class in RP threads, or, those nations meant to show the infallible nature of ones chosen political doctrine. In my opinion, the ‘Ultra pure esoteric hitlerism’ utopia is just as irritating as the ‘perfect anarcho pink communism femboy’ utopias. I have made my fair share of nations that are power trips for politics and just...power (I was both younger and dumber), so, take my opinion with a grain of salt, or a whole bag of it.

One cliche I want to see more of is settings that incorporate multiple players, I’m doing one with a few IRL buddies, and we plan to run a Cyberpunk 2020 game in it. A second cliche is retro-futurism or alt-tech scenarios, I have yet to see a China that uses lab grown brains for super computers, or an (active) Diesel punk or clock punk nation.

Thank you for coming to my Ted talk, I apologize for my rambling nature and any offence given.

by Socialist Macronesia » Wed May 19, 2021 8:33 pm

Drongonia wrote:
Dayganistan wrote:When people do all kinds of posts about far right stuff under the guise of RP and all of their RP posts are about banning antifa or being anti LGBT, you just know it's their IRL views.

Nah not really.


It honestly depends on how it's done. If it's a well written thread that explores the intricacies and nuances of such a medium, then it's usually not their own views. But there's not very many of those. A majority of them are just one line "we kill all the gays!" type of stuff. And frankly, I think that's the thing people miss: you can say something's not your real views all you want, but A. your assholery... err... poor taste still shows through, and B. just because you say something isn't your real world view doesn't mean that you aren't just lying. That's not just a free pass to kill as many ethnic groups as you want in your RPs just to get the same five word responses of "we are disappointed in you" or war declarations that never seem to be brought up again.

Well written genocide gets a pass. Not only does it handle the situation in good taste while not shying away from some of the more thought-provoking and in-depth content that might seem more controversial, but is still handled in a way that makes it clear that this is in fact supposed to be a bad thing, and most ordinary people within the story can comprehend that, rather than just being mindless workers of the state with no internal morals or ethics. They may be able and/or willing to put those away in times of conflict when they get carried away or get orders they must follow, but the ordinary person, including soldiers, have no desire to murder every LGBT+ individual they come across. They may not necessarily like them or might think they're "weird," but there's a difference between "they're a little bit different" and "they're a subhuman group that I will help eradicate." In a poorly written RP, like most on this subject, they assume everyone does what they're ordered to do with no questions asked.
Currently in the process of revamping all of my lore, including my signature. It's gonna probably take a while, better make yourself comfortable.
